Answer this question with the single letter for the correct answer only. Several figures can be made by attaching two equilateral triangles to the regular pentagon $ABCDE$ in two of the five positions shown. How many non-congruent figures can be constructed in this way?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I;
A=(10,0);
B=(0,0);
C=(-3.1,9.5);
D=(5,15.4);
I=(13.1,9.5);
draw(A--B--C--D--I--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--B--(5,-8.7)--cycle,dashed);
draw(A--I--(19.8,2.1)--cycle,dashed);
draw(C--B--(-9.8,2.1)--cycle,dashed);
draw(I--D--(14.15,19.4)--cycle,dashed);
draw(D--C--(-4.15,19.4)--cycle,dashed);
label("$A$",A,SE);
label("$B$",B,SW);
label("$C$",C,W);
label("$E$",I,E);
label("$D$",D,N);
[/asy]
A) 2
B) 4

Answer this question with the single letter for the correct answer only. Markov plays a game for three turns. On each turn, he either rolls a fair, six sided die or flips a fair coin. If he rolls a 1 or 2 on the die, he will switch to the coin on the next turn, and if he flips a tails on the coin, he will switch to the die on the next turn. If Markov starts by rolling the die, what is the probability that he will flip the coin on the third turn?
A) \frac{7}{18}
B) \frac{7}{20}

 Yes, I’m sure. The binomial coefficient  

\[
\binom{8}{6} = \frac{8!}{6!\,(8-6)!}
           = \frac{8!}{6!\,2!}
           = \frac{8\times7}{2}
           = 28.
\]

So the correct choice is **A**.

Answer this question with the single letter for the correct answer only. In the coordinate plane, let $F = (4,0).$  Let $P$ be a point, and let $Q$ be the projection of the point $P$ onto the line $x = \frac{25}{4}.$  The point $P$ traces a curve in the plane, so that
\[\frac{PF}{PQ} = \frac{4}{5}\]for all points $P$ on the curve.  Find the area of the region formed by the curve.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair P, F, Q;

F = (4,0);
P = (5*Cos(60),3*Sin(60));
Q = (25/4,3*Sin(60));

draw(F--P--Q);
draw((25/4,-1)--(25/4,3),dashed);

dot("$F$", F, S);
dot("$P$", P, W);
dot("$Q$", Q, E);

label("$x = \frac{25}{4}$", (25/4,-1), S);
[/asy]
A) 15 \pi
B) 16 \pi

Answer this question with the single letter for the correct answer only. Fourteen white cubes are put together to form the figure on the right.  The complete surface of the figure, including the bottom, is painted red.  The figure is then separated into individual cubes.  How many of the individual cubes have exactly four red faces?

[asy]
size(150);
pair a=(1,0),b=(0,1),c=(0.45,0.4);

void drawcube(pair loc){
     filldraw(loc+b--loc--loc+a--loc+a+c--loc+a+b+c--loc+b+c--cycle,white);
     draw(loc+b--loc+a+b--loc+a+b+c^^loc+a+b--loc+a);
}

pair location[]={origin,b,a,2a,3a,3a+b,-c,3a-c,-2c,-2c+b,-2c+a,-2c+2a,-2c+3a,-2c+3a+b};

for(int i; i<14;++i){
   drawcube(location[i]);
}


[/asy]
A) 6
B) 5
